fields.description:
This is the offending line:

{code}
#!c++

std::string(it.begin(), it.end())
{code}

Breaks the syntax when viewed in Bitbucket&#x27;s web viewer. Attached a screenshot to show.

h2. Examples
h3. Plain text URL
{code}
#!text
https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!
{code}

* https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!
* *works*: no

h3. Plain text URL with additional parameter
{code}
#!text
https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!&status=new  
{code}

* https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!&status=new
* *works*: (yes, but different meaning)
* This also means exclamation mark is working inside URLs in general.

h3. Inline link (URL link text)
{code}
#!text
[https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!](↵
https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!)
{code}

* [https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues%3Fresponsible%3D%21]
* *works*: no

h3. Inline link (URL link text omitting trailing non-alpha chars)
{code}
#!text
[https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible](↵
https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!)
{code}

* [https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues%3Fresponsible%3D%21]
* *works*: no!
* This even eats up the trailing non-alpha chars in the original () URL.

h3. Inline link (different link text)
{code}
#!text
[bitbucket.org issues: someone responsible](↵
https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!)
{code}

* [bitbucket.org issues: someone responsible|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues%3Fresponsible%3D%21] (_nb. target filter not working, see BCLOUD-8779_)
* *works*: yes

h3. Inline link (link text endind with exclamation mark)
{code}
#!text
[shout!](https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=!)
{code}

* [shout!|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues%3Fresponsible%3D%21]
* *works*: yes

h3. Plain text URL with HTML entity code
{code}
#!text
https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=&#33;
{code}

* https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=&#33;
* *works*: no

h3. Inline link (URL link text with HTML entity code)
{code}
#!text
[https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=&#33;](↵
https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=&#33;)
{code}

* [https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues?responsible=&#33;|https://bitbucket.org/site/master/issues%3Fresponsible%3D%26#33%3B]
* *works*: no

According to [Babelmark 2|http://johnmacfarlane.net/babelmark2/] it should not be Python-Markdown&#x27;s fault (which [is supposedly used here|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BITBUCKET/Mark%2Bup%2Bcomments]).

I suppose leaving punctuation behind links alone got a bit wild there?

----
{{[component: markdown]}}

so it appears creating a link as so

{code}
 [foo](/bar)
{code}

creates this url

{code}
 https://bitbucket.org/bar
{code}

in a wiki however this is actually a little annoying, it&#x27;d be nice if we could set a base url, in wiki settings, for relative urls, perhaps with some templating so that I could the original pattern would resolve (in my case) to

{code}
 https://bitbucket.org/xenoterracide/lm/wiki/bar
{code}

This is basically based on the idea that the relative url should be based on where the repository is deployed to, not the domain root. But I can see some people wanting it to be based on the domain root, so making it a configuration at the top of the wiki...

Currently if a HTML comment is encountered in a markdown file it is escaped and displayed literally.  Most[citation needed] implementations treat the comment as HTML and pass it through.

{code}
<!-- This gets escaped and displayed,
      but it would be nice if it was a HTML comment. -->
{code}

Additionally, some implementations completely remove comments with three leading dashes.

{code}
<!--- It would be nice if this was removed completely. -->
{code}
